    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "cb69b8b4_a51a34c0",
        "filename": "machine-db/appengine/database/setup/migrations/008_initialize_vms.up.sql",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 34,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-01-20T01:14:59Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "can a physical host and a VM have the same hostname on a given VLAN? If not, this model may be problematic. \n\nI noticed that VM and hosts are quite similar. Wouldn\u0027t it be simpler to add\n\n  parent_host_id int\n\nfield which is id of another host backing this host. This implies (parent_host_id IS NOT NULL) \u003d\u003e (host is virtual)",
      "revId": "d6f2f64e300f4b0d522914b390ef33990791da7f",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "5272c7d4_b65ef6fb",
        "filename": "machine-db/appengine/database/setup/migrations/008_initialize_vms.up.sql",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 34,
      "author": {
        "id": 1003211
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-01-20T02:23:29Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "They can\u0027t have the same name, agreed this isn\u0027t being addressed in the current schema.\n\nUnder the current schema I guess it\u0027s simpler, because we made hosts own all NICs on the machine. Originally, the hosts table needed a physical NIC to reference and there wouldn\u0027t be one for VMs. I guess I can do this. In fact, that means there can be a unified API for physical and virtual hosts, and the deciding factor between physical and virtual would be whether or not a parent host has been specified. What do you think?\n\nhttps://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/infra/luci/luci-go/+/877508",
      "parentUuid": "cb69b8b4_a51a34c0",
      "revId": "d6f2f64e300f4b0d522914b390ef33990791da7f",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "24c07e04_bc736887",
        "filename": "machine-db/appengine/database/setup/migrations/008_initialize_vms.up.sql",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 34,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-01-22T23:43:05Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Here are constraints that an ideal schema will guarantee:\n- host name is unique within VLAN\n- a host is either bare metal or virtual, not both, not none\n- one bare metal host per machine\n- for a VM to exist, a bare metal host on the same machine must exit\n- VM\u0027s machine equals machine of the backing bare metal host\n- VM\u0027s VLAN equals VLAN of the backing bare metal host\n\nAlso ideally every hosts row has machine_id column filled, so that we don\u0027t have to retrieve machine id via parent_id.\n\nnote that an inter-row constraint must be guaranteed by the database. I find it acceptable for the database schema NOT to guarantee an in-row constraint, e.g. \"a host is either metal or virtual\", because we can check that before inserting a row.\n\nthe problem with parent_id approach is that we can no longer have UNIQUE(machine_id) constraint, which means this schema does not guarantee that there is only one bare metal host per machine. We need to design a schema that will provide most guarantees.\n\nHere is something I came up with:\n+ add field parent_host_id int, nullable, FK to hosts(id)\n+ add field parent_machine_id int, nullable, FK to machines(id)\none of the fields must be non-NULL. DB cannot guarantee that, but we can check that when creating a host.\n\nWith those fields, other constraints can be guaranteed:\n- UNIQUE(parent_machine_id) guarantees that only one bare metal host exists on a machine\n- UNIQUE(vlan_id, name) guarantees name is unique within VLAN\n- FK hosts(parent_host_id, machine_id)-\u003ehosts(id, machine_id) guarantees that a bare metal host exists for this VM and its runs on the same machine\n- FK hosts(parent_host_id, vlan_id)-\u003ehosts(id, vlan_id) guarantees that a bare metal host exists for this VM and its runs in the same VLAN\n\nI don\u0027t like that this schema allows\n1) a host to be neither virtual nor bare metal\n2) a host to be both virtual and bare metal pointing, pointing to itself via parent_host_id. Creation of such rows may be challenging though, because you don\u0027t know the id of a new row to put it in the parent_host_id, but it is possible technically (via disabling FK constarints and then reenabling them).\n\nbut we can control that when creating a row and it is not a subject to race with other db clients.\n\nWDYT?",
      "parentUuid": "5272c7d4_b65ef6fb",
      "revId": "d6f2f64e300f4b0d522914b390ef33990791da7f",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "00daea78_a004c304",
        "filename": "machine-db/appengine/database/setup/migrations/008_initialize_vms.up.sql",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 34,
      "author": {
        "id": 1003211
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-01-23T00:52:25Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I\u0027m not sure it\u0027s necessary to have machine_id in a virtual host row. Assuming we don\u0027t need it, I believe we can fulfill the same subset of the ideal requirements with the addition of just one parent_host_id column. Then if machine_id \u003c\u003e NULL then the row is a physical host and if parent_host_id \u003c\u003e NULL then the row is a virtual host. Ideally the schema would enforce that machine_id \u003c\u003e NULL xor parent_host_id \u003c\u003e NULL, but I don\u0027t believe it can.\n\nThen the constraints would be:\n- UNIQUE(name, vlan_id). Enforces name uniqueness per VLAN.\n- UNIQUE(machine_id). Enforces at most one physical host per machine. My understanding is that NULLs are excluded, so this constraint will only apply when machine_id \u003c\u003e NULL.\n- FOREIGN KEY (parent_host_id, vlan_id) REFERENCES hosts(id, vlan_id). Enforces that the parent host being referenced exists on the same VLAN. My understanding is that if parent_host_id is NULL, this constraint won\u0027t apply, which is fine.\n\nI realize this is almost exactly the same as what you came up with, just with fewer columns and fewer foreign key constraints. When we fetch rows we will need an extra join to find the machine backing the physical host backing the VM.\n\nI guess that means we agree % having a NOT NULL machine_id column for easy lookup. I don\u0027t really care if we have this or not, but not having it will save us the FOREIGN KEY (parent_host_id, machine_id) constraint.\n\nAgreed that the xor condition has to be controlled in other ways. I think it\u0027s impossible to enforce with one table.",
      "parentUuid": "24c07e04_bc736887",
      "revId": "d6f2f64e300f4b0d522914b390ef33990791da7f",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
